  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the real danger of AI writing is not poor quality but plausible smoothness that masks a lack of genuine point of view. The author describes a personal shift from treating AI-generated drafts as finished artifacts to using AI as a \"pressure tool\" for organizing, interrogating, and generating alternatives—while reserving human judgment for the sharp, trust-earning parts of the text. Key technologies include GPT for lesson outlines, quiz prompts, and translation scaffolds, with a workflow that emphasizes friction over automation. The tone is a reflective, analytical narrative, framed by metaphors of \"brochure vs. experience,\" \"clay vs. bowl,\" and \"replacing mechanical parts, not self.\" The intended audience is technical writers, educators, and content creators grappling with AI integration.",
